        "title": "The gate scene — making redemption public and legal",
        "range": "4:1-8",
        "excerpt": "Now Boaz went up to the gate and sat down there, and behold, the close relative of whom Boaz spoke was passing by, so he said, \"Turn aside, friend, sit down here.\"",
        "body": "The chapter opens with a shift in venue that is theologically loaded. Chapter 3 happened at night on a threshing floor — a private space charged with risk and ambiguity. Chapter 4 happens at dawn in the city gate — Israel's most public legal venue. The same Boaz who told Ruth in 3:13 *if he will redeem you, good; let him redeem you* now follows through immediately. Note the narrative speed: Boaz *went up to the gate and sat down there* (4:1) — and the nearer redeemer *was passing by* in the very next clause. The book that has spent three chapters on providential timing now compresses providence into a single morning.\n\nBoaz's procedural rigor matters. He summons not the nearer redeemer alone but *ten men of the elders of the city* (4:2). Ten was the quorum required for legal action in Israelite custom (later codified in rabbinic tradition as *minyan*, but already operative here). He frames the transaction in two stages, withholding the Ruth-clause until the nearer redeemer has publicly committed to the field. This is not deception — it is forensic strategy. By the time *acquire Ruth the Moabitess* is added (4:5), the nearer redeemer must either back out publicly or accept the full cost publicly. Boaz forces a clean, witnessed resolution.\n\nThe nearer redeemer's response (4:6) reveals the spine of the chapter: *I cannot redeem it for myself, because I would jeopardize my own inheritance*. His reasoning is economic. Buying the field would normally augment his estate; but if Ruth's first son legally belongs to Mahlon's line (the *raise up the name* principle of 4:5), then the field will pass to that son rather than to the nearer redeemer's own heirs. He has just spent money on land his own children will not inherit. The cost-benefit no longer works. So he declines.\n\nThis is not a villain. The text does not condemn him. But it pointedly does not *name* him. *Peloni almoni* (4:1, often translated *friend* or *so-and-so*) is the Hebrew narrator's way of saying *anonymous person*. The man who chose his inheritance over the redemption of a dead brother's name is erased from the record. Boaz, who absorbed the cost, is named six times in the chapter and immortalized in the genealogy. The narrator's editorial silence speaks: redemption that does not cost the redeemer something is not redemption.\n\nThe sandal ceremony (4:7-8) seals the transfer. The narrator must explain it — *this was the custom in former times in Israel* — telling us he writes from a later vantage when the practice is obsolete. The removal of the sandal echoes Deuteronomy 25:7-10, the levirate refusal ceremony, where a refusing brother-in-law has his sandal removed in shame. Here the resonance is softer — no shame language is used — but the visible, tactile sign accomplishes what words alone cannot: it makes the legal transfer permanent and witnessed.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Sha'ar* (gate) is the standard term for Israel's judicial venue (cf. Deuteronomy 21:19; 22:15; 25:7). *Peloni almoni* (4:1) is a Hebrew idiom for an unnamed party — literally *so-and-so, such-and-such* — used elsewhere only at 1 Samuel 21:2 and 2 Kings 6:8. *Go'el* (kinsman-redeemer) carries the technical Levitical sense of Leviticus 25:25 — the nearest relative obligated to recover forfeited family land."
