        "title": "The redeemer's vow — preserving the name of the dead",
        "range": "4:9-12",
        "excerpt": "I have acquired Ruth the Moabitess, the widow of Mahlon, to be my wife in order to raise up the name of the deceased on his inheritance, so that the name of the deceased will not be cut off from his brothers or from the court of his birth place; you are witnesses today.",
        "body": "Boaz's declaration in 4:9-10 is the legal and theological climax of the chapter. He invokes the elders and *all the people* twice as witnesses (4:9, 10 — *you are witnesses today*), framing the act in maximally public terms. He names every dead man — *Elimelech and all that belonged to Chilion and Mahlon* (4:9) — and specifies Ruth's prior identity precisely: *the Moabitess, the widow of Mahlon* (4:10). Nothing is hidden. The transaction is performed in full daylight, with every relevant party named.\n\nThe purpose clause is decisive: *in order to raise up the name of the deceased on his inheritance, so that the name of the deceased will not be cut off* (4:10). The verb *cut off* (*karat*) is the language of covenant severance — the same root used when God *cuts a covenant* and when an unfaithful party is *cut off from his people* (Genesis 17:14; Exodus 12:15). Boaz acts so that Mahlon's name will not be *karat*-ed from Israel. The redeemer absorbs personal cost — his own first son will be legally Mahlon's heir, not Boaz's — so that a dead man's name persists in the covenant community.\n\nThis is gospel logic in seed form. The redeemer pays a price he is not obligated to pay, on behalf of someone who cannot pay anything, so that the dead man's name lives. Tim Keller has noted that Boaz models a substitutionary willingness: he takes on the foreign Moabite widow, the dead man's debt, and the field that will not enrich his own line — all so that another's name endures. He is not Christ — Christ is unique — but he stands as a real-historical type in the canonical line that produces Christ.\n\nThe community's blessing (4:11-12) interprets the act theologically. Three matriarchs are invoked: *Rachel and Leah, both of whom built the house of Israel* (4:11), and *Tamar* (4:12, alluding to Genesis 38, where Tamar herself secured the line of Judah through an unconventional and legally-charged path). The triple invocation is dense. Rachel and Leah produced the twelve tribes through difficult, often painful covenant fidelity. Tamar's name in particular is striking — she is invoked because her son Perez is the head of the genealogy that closes the chapter (4:18). The blessing implicitly recognizes that God's covenant line has always passed through women whose stories defied convention, including foreign women and women whose paths involved scandal. Ruth — *the Moabitess* — is now placed in their company.\n\nThe geographical specificity of *Ephrathah… Bethlehem* (4:11) is canonically loaded. Micah 5:2 will name *Bethlehem Ephrathah* as the birthplace of the One whose *goings forth are from of old, from everlasting* — the Messiah. The elders of Bethlehem in Ruth 4 speak a blessing whose fulfillment ultimately points beyond David to David's greater Son, born in the same town a thousand years later.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Heqim shem* (raise up the name, 4:5, 10) is the technical phrase from Deuteronomy 25:7 for the levirate duty — though strictly speaking the levir was the brother of the deceased, and Boaz is a more distant relative. The book applies levirate logic by extension to the kinsman-redeemer relationship. *Karat shem* (cut off the name, 4:10) is the inverse — the threat that the levirate institution exists to prevent."
