        "excerpt": "So Boaz took Ruth, and she became his wife, and he went in to her. And the Lord enabled her to conceive, and she gave birth to a son.",
        "body": "Verse 13 is the most compressed verse in the book. Marriage, consummation, divine action, conception, and birth are folded into a single sentence. The narrator who has lingered for four chapters over harvest fields and threshing floors now accelerates through the events most modern readers would expect to be developed at length. The reason is theological: this verse is not about the events; it is about the *agent*.\n\nFor three and a half chapters, the LORD has worked through providential coincidence. Ruth *happened to come* to Boaz's field (2:3 — and the Hebrew there is pointedly ironic, marking what looks like chance but is providence). Boaz noticed her. The harvest extended. The nearer redeemer passed by at just the right moment. But until 4:13, the narrator has not directly named the LORD as the cause of a single concrete event. Here he does: *the Lord enabled her to conceive*. Hebrew: *wayyitten YHWH lah herayon* — literally *and the LORD gave to her conception*.\n\nThis is theologically deliberate. Ruth had been married to Mahlon for ten years in Moab and remained childless (1:4-5). Whatever the cause — the text does not specify — she was not biologically incapable; she was waiting for the right covenant moment. The same God who was hidden behind every providential turn now openly opens her womb. The book's theology of *hesed* (covenant loyalty) and providence is here finally named: behind every faithful human act in this story, the LORD has been working.\n\nCalvin's reading of this verse is characteristic: God's hidden providence and named action are not two different modes but two perspectives on the same governance. What the narrator calls *coincidence* in chapter 2 and *the LORD enabled* in chapter 4 are the same divine work, viewed from different angles. The chapter has earned the right to name God directly because the whole book has been preparing the reader to see Him.\n\nThe child is also theologically deliberate. He is born to Ruth, but the community will call him Naomi's son (4:17). He is legally Mahlon's son under the *raise up the name* logic (4:5, 10). And canonically, he is the grandfather of David (4:17, 22). One child carries four genealogical relationships, and all of them are real. The text resists modern individualism: this son belongs to multiple lines because covenant life is corporate, generational, and legally structured."
