        "body": "The chapter's emotional resolution is delivered not by the narrator and not by Boaz, but by *the women* of Bethlehem (4:14). This is the same chorus who in 1:19 had said *Is this Naomi?* when she returned from Moab — bitter, empty, husband-less and son-less. Now they speak the blessing the book has been waiting for: *Blessed is the Lord who has not left you without a redeemer today, and may his name become famous in Israel* (4:14). Note carefully — they call the *child* the redeemer (*go'el*), not Boaz. The legal redemption of vv. 1-12 has produced a redemptive *outcome* — a child who will sustain Naomi and carry her line forward.\n\nVerse 15 names Ruth in language that should stop the reader: *your daughter-in-law, who loves you and is better to you than seven sons, has given birth to him*. In a patrilineal culture where sons were the measure of a woman's worth and *seven* was the proverbial maximum of blessing (1 Samuel 2:5; Job 1:2), to declare a *Moabite daughter-in-law* better than seven Israelite sons is staggering hyperbole. The community of Bethlehem has come to see Ruth not as a foreign threat but as the agent of Naomi's redemption — and they say so publicly.\n\nVerse 16 is one of the book's tenderest sentences: *Then Naomi took the child and laid him in her lap, and became his nurse*. The Hebrew *omenet* (nurse, attendant) does not necessarily mean she breastfed him — it means she became his caregiver, the one who held him on her bosom. The empty widow of 1:21 — who said *I went out full, but the LORD has brought me back empty* — is now full again, holding her grandson. The verbal echo is intentional. *Empty* and *full* are the polar terms of Naomi's arc, and the LORD has reversed it.\n\nThen verse 17 delivers the book's most surprising line: *The neighbor women gave him a name, saying, \"A son has been born to Naomi!\" So they named him Obed*. The child is born to Ruth (4:13), but the women say he is born *to Naomi*. The grammar is striking but theologically precise: this is a redemption that restores Naomi's line, not just Ruth's. The covenant promise to Elimelech's house (preserved through Ruth and Boaz's son) lands legally and emotionally on Naomi. She is the mother of the line that produces David.\n\nThe name *Obed* (עוֹבֵד) means *one who serves* or *servant*. It is a humble name — not a triumphal one. The boy who will become the grandfather of Israel's greatest king is named *servant*. This is canonical foreshadowing: the line that produces the King is a line that learns to serve, and the King himself will be born in this same town to be the Servant of the LORD (Isaiah 53; Mark 10:45)."
