        "excerpt": "Now these are the generations of Perez: to Perez was born Hezron… and to Obed was born Jesse, and to Jesse, David.",
        "body": "The chapter's final five verses are the canonical destination of the entire book. *Now these are the generations of Perez* (4:18) uses the formal *toledot* formula (*'elleh toledot*) that marks the structural seams of Genesis (Genesis 2:4; 5:1; 6:9; 10:1; 11:10; 25:12, 19; 36:1, 9; 37:2). By deploying this formula, the narrator is signaling that Ruth's story belongs not merely to the era of the judges but to the foundational genealogical structure of Israel itself. This is canonical placement.\n\nTen names are given: Perez, Hezron, Ram, Amminadab, Nahshon, Salmon, Boaz, Obed, Jesse, David. The structure is symmetrical — Boaz stands at position seven (the number of completion), David at position ten (the number of fullness). Some commentators (e.g., Daniel Block, *Judges, Ruth*, NAC) argue that the genealogy is selective rather than exhaustive — the time span from Perez to David is too long for only ten generations — but the selection is theologically intentional, not historically careless. Old Testament genealogies routinely compress to feature significant figures.\n\nThe genealogy answers the question the book has been quietly asking from 1:1. The book opens with *in the days when the judges judged* (1:1) — a period the book of Judges itself summarizes with the refrain *there was no king in Israel; everyone did what was right in his own eyes* (Judges 17:6; 21:25). Ruth's question is implicit: where is God in such days? The genealogy answers: God was raising up the king. Behind every harvest field, every threshing-floor decision, every gate transaction, the LORD was bringing forth David.\n\nAnd canonically, the line does not stop with David. Matthew 1:5-6 picks up the same genealogy: *Salmon was the father of Boaz by Rahab, and Boaz was the father of Obed by Ruth, and Obed the father of Jesse, and Jesse the father of David the king*. Matthew adds Rahab (Joshua 2; 6) — another foreign woman in the line — and carries the genealogy forward through David to Jesus Christ. Two foreign women, a Canaanite prostitute and a Moabite widow, stand in the canonical line of the Messiah. The gospel of God's grace to outsiders is already written into the book of Ruth.\n\nThe book that began with a famine in Bethlehem ends with David, and the canonical horizon points to the Greater David — born in the same Bethlehem (Micah 5:2; Matthew 2:1; Luke 2:4-7) — who would be the true Kinsman-Redeemer. Boaz redeemed land, a name, and a widow at personal cost. Jesus Christ redeemed His people *by His own blood* (Acts 20:28; 1 Peter 1:18-19), absorbing infinite cost so that His Bride — including every spiritual Moabite — would be brought into the covenant family. The book of Ruth is not merely a charming pastoral; it is the prologue to the gospel.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Toledot* (generations, 4:18) is the structural formula of Genesis — its appearance here intentionally links Ruth's story to the patriarchal narrative arc. *David* (דָּוִד) is the final word of the book in Hebrew — the climactic name everything has built toward."
